3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates every hour based on the premium/discount between perpetual and index prices sourced from Chainlink oracles. Funding payments occur automatically between long and short positions, with rates typically ranging from -0.01% to +0.01% per hour. The decentralized nature means funding rates can deviate significantly from CEX counterparts, especially during oracle lag periods. GLP liquidity providers effectively take the opposite side of net open interest, creating additional arbitrage dynamics."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ENA","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA (Ethena) perpetuals on GMX present compelling arbitrage opportunities due to the token's synthetic dollar nature and high volatility around yield farming events. The pair often exhibits funding rate premiums during Ethena protocol updates or sUSDe yield announcements. Lower liquidity compared to major pairs can amplify funding rate movements, creating profitable arbitrage windows."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA/USDT on GMX has shown pronounced funding rate spikes during Ethena ecosystem developments, with rates reaching +0.05% hourly during major announcements. The oracle-based pricing creates lag effects, particularly during rapid ENA price movements, leading to sustained funding premiums. Weekend periods typically see reduced volatility but can maintain elevated funding rates due to lower arbitrage activity. The pair's correlation with broader DeFi sentiment creates predictable funding patterns around governance proposals and yield updates."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-DEX arbitrage opportunities emerge when GMX funding rates diverge from other perpetual platforms due to oracle dependencies and lower liquidity. Long funding rate arbitrage becomes profitable when ENA experiences positive momentum, as GMX often sustains premiums longer than CEXs. Gas costs on Arbitrum make smaller arbitrage positions viable, with break-even funding rates around 0.005% hourly after fees. Market makers can exploit the 1-hour funding intervals by timing position entries around the funding timestamps."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Limitations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle dependency risk creates potential for price feed failures or manipulation, particularly during extreme market conditions affecting Chainlink data. GLP counterparty risk means traders effectively trade against the liquidity pool, which can lead to adverse selection during volatile periods. Higher trading fees (0.05-0.07%) compared to order book exchanges reduce net arbitrage profits and require higher funding rate differentials. Position sizing limitations exist due to available GLP liquidity and price impact on large trades, typically capping effective arbitrage size around $50K-100K."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does GMX's oracle pricing affect ENA funding rates?","answer":"GMX uses Chainlink oracles for price feeds, creating potential lag during rapid ENA movements. This can cause funding rates to remain elevated longer than on order book exchanges, as the perpetual price adjusts more slowly to spot movements."},{"question":"What's the typical funding rate range for ENA/USDT on GMX?","answer":"ENA/USDT funding rates typically range from -0.01% to +0.02% hourly, with spikes reaching +0.05% during Ethena ecosystem events. Negative rates are less common due to generally bullish sentiment around yield-bearing assets."},{"question":"Are there minimum position sizes for funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"While GMX has no explicit minimums, gas costs on Arbitrum make positions below $1,000 uneconomical for funding arbitrage. Optimal position sizes range from $5K-50K to balance fees against available liquidity."},{"question":"How does GLP liquidity affect large arbitrage positions?","answer":"Large positions may face price impact when opening/closing, as they trade against GLP pools rather than order books. This limits effective arbitrage size and requires careful position sizing to maintain profitability after slippage."}]}]
